@NODE FM_MainWindow "Falcon Math V0.1"
The main window is divided into three regions:-

       +------------------------------------------------------------------+
       | +--------------------------------------------------------------+ |
       | |                         STATUS BAR                           | |
       | +--------------------------------------------------------------+ |
       |                                                                  |
       | +--------------------------------------------------------------+ |
       | |                                                              | |
       | |                        @{"CURRENT EQUATION" link CurrentExp}                    	| |
       | |                                                              | |
       | +--------------------------------------------------------------+ |
       |                                                                  |
       | +--------------------------------------------------------------+ |
       | |                                                              | |
       | | @{" < ^ O v > " link BT_select  }@{" Otherside " link BT_othersid}@{" 1/x <=> x-ą" link BT_reciproc}@{" Both Sides" link BT_bothside}@{" Multiply  " link BT_multiply}	| |
       | | @{" Factorize " link BT_factoriz}@{" Substitute" link BT_substitu}@{" Evaluate   " link BT_evaluate}@{" Simplify  " link BT_simplify}@{"  Group    " link BT_group   }	| |
       | | @{" Diff'ate  " link BT_diffrate}@{" Integrate " link BT_integrte}@{"   Trig     " link BT_trigonmt}@{" Algebra   " link BT_algebra }@{" New Expr  " link BT_newexpr }	| |
       | |                                                             	| |
       | |                                                             	| |
       | +--------------------------------------------------------------+ |
       |                                                               	  |
       +------------------------------------------------------------------+

There is also a @{"menu strip" link Menu} to access the more esoteric features.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_select  "Selection Gadgets"

Normaly to select terms in the @{"CURRENT EQUATION" link CurrentExp} you simply click on the
term in question. However in some situations this is awkward.

These five small buttons provide an alternative way of selecting sections of the
equation in the main window.

The central button selects the whole expression.

The Down arrow narrows the selection, Up broadens the selection.

Left and right cycle through all possible selections at this level.

These buttons have keyboard Shortcuts:-

	Broaden Selection = 8
	Narrow  Selection = 2
	Cycle Left        = 4
	Cycle Right       = 6
	Select All        = 5
	
{ the shortcuts are based on the numeric keypad. }

@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_OtherSid "Other Side"

Button Description: Other Side Button

This moves a term to the other side of an equation.

For this to be possible there must be an equation (rather than an expression)
in the window and the term must be transferable to the other side in a single
operation.

For example 

		A+ B*C = D

The A can be moved to the other side (to give B*C=D-A), as can B*C, but not B
or C independantly.
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_bothside "To Both Sides"
This function allows you to perform an operation on both sides of an equation.

After pressing the button a window will appear.

Select the operation to perform in the upper of the two cycle gadgets. This 
can be one of ADD, SUBTRACT, MULTIPLY, DIVIDE.

Then enter the argument in the string gadget at the top.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CurrentExp "Current Expression"

This window contains the expression that you are currently working on.

Parts of the expression that have been selected are shown in white, other
parts are in black.

To select a part of the expression click on it with the mouse.

* To select an individual variable or constant  (eg "a" or "1") click on the
  symbol itself.

* To select several terms multiplied together click on the space between them
  or click on one then on the Up Arrow Button.
  
* To select the contents of a bracket click on the bracket

* To select terms joined by an operator click on the operator ( eg to select
  "a+b" click on the "+"

@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_newexpr "Entering a new expression"

This button allows you to enter a new expression, or replace parts of an old
one.

To start off it is the only enabled button.

When pressed a requester will appear allowing you to enter a new expression.

Expressions are entered in fairly normal algebraic notation, but note

* Multiplication is denoted by `*', division by `/', exponentiation by `^'

* Multi letter variable names ARE allowed. Although they are entered all on
  one level they will be displayed as subscripts in the expression window.

* The `*' for multiplication can be missed out when no confusion would arrise
  for example:-
  
      OK: 2a  
          (a+b)(a-b)    
          2a(6c-3)

  NOT OK: 2ab           means 2 times a_subscript_b
          2a/b*c        means ( 2 times a divided by b ) all times c

* Brackets can be () or {}.
  The computer will automaticaly add/remove () brackets when appropriate.
  The computer will not remove {} brackets (exception - @{link "simplify" BT_simplify}.

* @{"Functions" link functions} are allowed, brackets are only needed where confusion could
  arrise. A function name must be followed by an open bracket or a space.

@ENDNODE
@NODE functions "Functions"

FalconMath understands the following functions:-

	sin              }
	cos              }  All
	tan              }  arguments
	arcsin           }  in
	arccos           }  radians.
	arctan           }
	ln               <== log to base e
	exp
	log	             log to the base 10.
	
Function names must be followed by a space or an open bracket.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_reciproc "1/x to x-ą"
This function switches between alternate ways of writing the same thing.

So for example 1/x can be written as x-ą.

This function can also be used to change a whole expression.

So		a-c = b-d

will be converted to c-a = d-b
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_multiply "Multiply Out"

This is used to multiply out a bracket.

It can be used on terms of the form (...)(....) and also on (......)^n

For large expressions this function can take some time - and produce
very long expressions. (try (a+b)^9)
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_factoriz

This is used to remove common factors from a series of terms.

For example to convert a*b + a*c  into a(b+c)

It can also be used on polynomial expressions where the coeficients
are constants. Eg   x˛+3x+2  can be converted to (x+1)(x+2)

After pressing the button the computer will attempt to determine what
factors could be taken out. If you want to change the selection then
edit the string in the requester.

@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_substitu "Substitute"

This allows you to replace all occurances of an expression with another
expression. Select the term to replace and click on Substitute. The
requester that appears allows you to enter a new expression from the
keyboard or to retrieve one from the @{"storyboard" link storyboard}.

While this CAN be used to replace expressions they must be of
EXACTLY the same form as the origional. If you substitute 'u' for 'x+1'
don't expect the program to replace 'x' with 'u-1'. To perform this
form of substitution you should replace 'x' with 'u-1' then call
SIMPLIFY to remove any excess constants.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_evaluate "Evaluate"

This can be used to evaluate the highlighted expression.

It does NOT work on equations ( ie if there is an equals sign in the
expression then this function will always return zero ). If you have an
equation in the window then highlight one side of it to evaluate.

The program will need to know what values to substitute in for any
variables used in the expression. When you have entered these then
press "EVALUATE" and the expression will be calculated.

There is also the option to @{"graph" link graph} the function. The graph
works on the same values for variables as the evaluator.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_simplify "Simplify"

This button attempts to remove any redundant parts in the main window.
Things such as 'a-a' will be replaced with zero, 'a*a' with a˛ and so
on.

It is best to press this button occasionaly during work as it removes
any little ineficiencies that may have built up.

Simplify can also be used to remove a pair of "squigely" {} brackets.
Click on the bracket then press SIMPLIFY. Squigly brackets are unlike
round () brackets in that the computer will not normaly remove them
when they are redundant. This allows you too group terms together.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_group "Group"

This is used to collect together terms.

This may be for clarity or it may be that you want to perform an
operation on some terms but not others.

Select the narrowest group of terms wider than the group you want
to collect then press the GROUP button. A requester will appear to allow
you to select which terms to group. The group can be unmade by selecting
the group and pressing SIMPLIFY.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_diffrate "Differentiate"

This is used to differentiate an expression.

It is disabled unless a valid keyfile is present.

To change the variable to differentiate with respect to use the menu
item Storyboard/Variables. The variable specified as "Main Variable"
will be used.

Any other varaibles marked as non-constant will be differentiated
explicitly. (eg "y" differentiates to "dy/dx" if "x" is the main vairiable).
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_integrte "Integrate"

This is used to integrate an expression.

The integration system used is fairly basic, It is often nececary to
"fiddle" about with the expression before it can be integrated.

The computer only knows a limited number of integrals. If a term is not
composed of one of its known integrals, or a composite of several then
an error will be reported.

The integrals known are:  (? = Integral of)

	?(A + B)	==>	?A + ?B
	?c.f(x)	==>	c . ?f(x)
	?f(x)dx	==> ?f(u)du.dx/du		where u=ax+b, a,b constants
	
	

 It will attempt
to map the given expression onto one or more of its standard integrals

Currently it is not yet implemented.

To change the variable integration is with respect to use the menu item
Stroyboard/Variables and edit the "Main Variable" item.

@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_algebrac "Algebraic Identities"

This button is used to apply an algebraic manipulation to an expression -
for example partial fraction expansion or completing a square.

Currently no manipulations have been implemented.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BT_trigonmt "Trigonometric Identities"

This button is used to apply a trig identity to a term.

Currently implemented trig identities are:-

	sin (a+b)  -->   sin a cos b + sin b cos a
	cos (a+b)  -->   sin a sin b - cos a cos b
	sin (n*a)  -->   sin ( (n-1)a + a)				n=+ve int
	cos (n*a)  -->   cos ( (n-1)a + a)				n=+ve int
	sin˛x+cos˛x-->   1
	tan (x)    -->   sin x / cos x
	
	and a few others.
	
More identities will be implemented in the near future.
@ENDNODE
@NODE graph

This allows an expression to be graphed.

To access the graph select evaluate and specify the values to use for
any constant variables.

Then select GRAPH. A new requester wil appear to allow you to specify
the ranges of the X and Y axis, and a choice of which variable to use 
on the X axis.

Press OK and the graph will be drawn. Use the menus on the graph screen
to return to the main program.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Menu
A menu strip is also availible which allows access to some of the less
frequently used parts of FalconMath.

	Project
		New		Clear the @{"Storyboard" link storyboard}
		Save		Store the @{"Storyboard" link storyboard} to disk
		Load		Retreve a @{"Storyboard" link storyboard} from disk
		About		Tells you about the program and how to register.
		Quit
		
	Storyboard
		View		View the @{"Storyboard" link storyboard}
		Highlight	Mark the current equation a key equation.
		Variables	Specify how each symbol is to be used for calculus routines.
		
	Extras
		Calculator	@{"Other tools" @ link OtherTools}
		Simultaneous	@{"Other tools" @ link OtherTools}
		Polynomial	@{"Other tools" @ link OtherTools}
@ENDNODE
@NODE storyboard
Falcon Math maintains a "storyboard" charting the progress of your equations.
Every time an equation is changed a copy is placed on the storyboard. with a
description of how it was derived.

Select Menu Storyboard/view to display the storyboard.

Double Click on an entry to copy it to the main window.

The storyboard can be loaded and saved from the project menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE OtherTools "Other Tools"
Three little "standard" mathematical programs are built into Falconmath.
These are accessed from the "Extras" menu.

		Calculator	A simple calculator
		Simultaneous	Solve a set of linear simultaneous equations
		Polynomial	Find the roots of a polynomial equation.

These tools are rather basic. They are only included for convenience.

The polynomial solver gives rather mystereous results if there are any 
complex roots. Therefore you lways check any results it gives you.
A better way of finding the roots of a polynomial is to enter it into the
main window and press Factorize.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Tutorial

Here is a brief "how to" guide to using FalconMath.

	@{"  Entering an expression    " link TUT_EnterExpr}
	@{"  Highlighting Terms        " link TUT_Highlight}
	@{"  Manipulating expressions  " link TUT_Manipulate}
	@{"  Evaluate and Graph        " link TUT_Evaluate}
	@{"  Reviewing your work       " link TUT_Storyboard}
	@{"  Substitution              " link TUT_Substitute}
	@{"  Trig & Calculus           " link TUT_Trig}
@ENDNODE
@NODE TUT_EnterExpr

Click On the "New Expr" button. A window will appear with a space to allow
you to enter the equation (or expression) you want to work on.

Enter the equation all on one line, use brackets where nececary. Don't put 
spaces into the equation except after a function name. 

Use brackets after a function when ambiguity might arise.
For example the computer will regard @{B} cos 3x @{UB} as @{B} (cos 3)(x) @{UB}
rather than as @{B} cos (3x) @{UB}

To show raising to a power use ^   (SHIFT+6 on UK keyboard)

Use * to indicate multiplication. The * can be omitted when no confusion could
arise, for example @{B} 3x @{UB}@, but not @{B}ab@{UB} - which will be regarded
as a_subscript_b.

So for example to enter the equation

						y = sin˛ x
						    ------
						    (x+a)ł
						    
you would type   y=(sin x)^2/((x+a)^3)

After pressing enter the expression should appear in the main window. If there
are any errors then press New Expr again and make changes.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TUT_Highlight
Once an expression has been entered you need to say what you want the
computer to do with it. Often this will involve focusing on one part of the
expression.

The simplest way of selecting something is to click on it. Every mouse click 
will select the smallest independant part of the expression that incorporate
the mouse position.

This takes a little bit of getting used to.

If the display shows:-

						y = sin˛ x
						    ------
						    (x+a)ł
						    
	click on     ˛    to select  ˛
	click on     x    to select  x
	click on    sin   to select sin˛x
	click on     +    to select (x+a)
	click on     =    to select everything

This can make some terms difficult to select, for example to select (x+a)ł
you need to click somewhere between the ) and the ł.

For this reason there are 4 small buttons with arrows and one with a circle.
The up arrow widens the selected area, down arrow narrows it. Left and right
cycle between all terms at the same level in the expression.

The circle button selects the whole expression.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TUT_Manipulate

Once you have mastered selecting terms manipulating them with FalconMath
is pretty easy. Just select the term then click on the operation. Where more
parameters are needed requesters will pop up to ask for it.

A few things to note however:-

	*	OtherSide can only work when there is exactly one equals sign 
		in the equation, and the term to be moved is one level lower 
		than the equals in the expression hierachy. Occasionaly you 
		may get an awkward case like:-
		
				- x = a + b
				
		and the computer refuses to allow you to move the x saying it does
		not apply to the whole of one side. This is because the program sees
		it as -(x) rather than as 0-x. In this case select the whole 
		expression then press the "1/x<->x-ą" button, then try again.
		
	*	The "1/x<->x-ą" button toggles between different representations of
		something. for example 
			0.33333		<->		1/3
			a/b		<->		ab-ą
			-a=b-c	<->		a=c-b
		Select the area which just includes the whole the term to be changed.
		
	*	Multiply out can take a long time for large polynomials. It can also
        produce some quite unwieldy expressions.( try (a+b+c)^10 and see what
        I mean.)
        
	*	The Factorizer is not terribly bright, it handles polynomals where the
		terms are all numbers, and terms like a*b+a*c but occasionaly gets
		a little confused with finding greatest common divisors ( eg when
		converting 6x+9y into 3(2x+3y) ).

		If you are not happy with the facotors it suggests then change the
		contents of the box that it produces.

 	*	Use the group button to isolate terms when you cannot select them
 		by normal methods. This is particularly for the factorizer. For
 		example if you want to factorize x+a*b+a*c to get x+a(b+c) you will
 		first need to group a*b+a*c apart from the x, then factorize the
 		squigly bracket. The factorizer will automaticaly remove the
 		squigly brackets if it thinks that they were only put there for its
 		benefit.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TUT_Evaluate

@{B}BUG@{UB} The evaluator and grapher only works for expressions not equations
If there are any equals signs in sight then the results of the evaluator
may become pure fiction.

A window will appear with boxes for each of the varaibles you have used in
expressions so far. Enter values into these boxes for the variables, then
press evaluate to calculate the answer.

After setting the values for all constants press GRAPH to draw a graph
A new window pops up with options to specify which variable will be swept
for the X-Axis, the minimum and maximum values for each axis and the axis
titles. Once the parameters have been set click OK to plot the graph.

Use the menu strip on the graph screen to save or print (might not yet 
be implmented) the graph. ( if print doesn't work then you will have to save
the graph, then load it into dpaint or something
@ENDNODE
@NODE TUT_Storyboard
FalconMath keeps a record of your manipulations of an equation. At any stage
you can go back to an earlier equation, or view your progress.

This record is called the storyboard. The storyboard window can be opened by
taking the Munu Storyboard/View. Double-click on an equation to copy it to the
main window.

The storyboard can be saved by the Save item on the menu. The result is 
basicaly a simple ASCII file which should be possible to load into any
wordproccessor.

Anyone who has seen an earlier version of FalconMath may recall a grpahical
report writer linked to the storyboard. This has been removed - hopefully
such facilities will be availible in FalconWord when it is released.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TUT_Substitute
There are two commands built into FalconMath to substitute into equations.

If you select a section of an expression then press NewExpr you can 
replace part of an expression with another expression.

A more advanced function is Substitute. Select a term then press substitute
a window will open to ask what you want to substitute for the term. Either
enter a value or look up an expression from the storyboard.

All references to the initialy selected term will be replaced with the
new term.

NOTE the substitute function ONLY performs substitution. It does not
rearange. So if you substitute in (x+y) for (a+b) the computer will
not replace (a) with (x+y-b).
@ENDNODE
@NODE TUT_Trig
Trig and Calculus functions are currently under development.

Currently Differentiate works on most equations, PLEASE TREAT ITS OUTPUT
WITH SOME CAUTION - IT HAS NOT BEEN COMPREHENSIVELY TESTED.

Trig only knows a few trig identities. It can apply:-
	SIN (a+b) 	==> SIN a COS b + COS a SIN b
	COS (a+b)   ==>	COS a COS b - SIN a SIN b
	SIN (n*a)	==>	SIN ( (n-1)a + a)	}then apply SIN (A+B)
	COS (n*a)	==>	COS ( (n-1)a + a)	}then apply COS (A+B)
	
Integration is fairly limited but does seem to work OK.
	
These functions will be enhanced in later versions of the program.

These functions need to know how to treat each symbol. The menu item
storyboard/variables allows you to specify if a symbol is a variable or
a constant, and which variable to use as the principle variable ( to
differentiate with respect to, for example).
@ENDNODE
